<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-241-152  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 241 152.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  May 1989 v8 n7 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Channel One: one pilot school gives a thumbs up. (Channel Oneteenage TV news program)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gosewisch, Bill Morgan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The pilot program for Channel One, the teenage television newsprogram geared toward schools, received good marks in an initialfive-week trial.andP;  Six schools from all over the countryparticipated in the trial period that took place during March andApril of 1989.andP;  News and commercials were broadcast for 12 minutesper day.andP;  The pilot schools received approximately $50,000 worthof equipment: color monitors, a satellite dish, a VCR, and afacsimile machine.andP;  Concerns were evident regarding the concept ofallowing commercials to be broadcast into schools, but the qualityof the news productions were good.andP;  The students' attention spanstended to drift, depending on the content and their level ofinterest in the program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     NewsEducationBroadcastingPilot ProjectsSecondary Schools.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>